<h2>
  About
</h2>
<p>
  The Pareidoscope is work in progress, so there might be considerable
  changes in future releases.
</p>
<h3>
  Author
</h3>
<p>
  The Pareidoscope has been developed by <a target="_blank"
  href="http://purl.org/thomas.proisl/">Thomas Proisl</a> as part of
  his dissertation project on patterns of lexicogrammatical
  interaction.
</p>
<h3>
  Name
</h3>
<p>
  The name Pareidoscope is meant to derive from Greek παράδειγμα
  (<i>paradeigma</i>) &ldquo;pattern&rdquo;, εἶδος (<i>eidos</i>)
  &ldquo;form, shape&rdquo; and σκοπέω (<i>skopeō</i>)
  &ldquo;examine&rdquo;.
</p>
<h3>
  Data
</h3>
<p>
  The publicly available web version uses a small sample of the
  English Wikipedia XML dump from 2010/03/12. To be precise, the
  corpus contains 222,642,217 tokens corresponding to 3,104,672 types
  in 14,368,722 sentences. There are 1,550,975,762 part-of-speech
  n-gram tokens with 1 &#x2264; n &#x2264; 9 in the corpus. They
  correspond to 183,724,952 part-of-speech n-gram types.
</p>
<p>
  The corpus has been tagged with <a target='_blank'
  href='http://code.google.com/p/hunpos/'>HunPos</a>, an open source
  reimplementation of the well-known <a target='_blank'
  href='http://www.coli.uni-saarland.de/~thorsten/tnt/'>TnT
  tagger</a>.  The tagger has been trained on the BNC Sampler, a two
  million words subset of the British National Corpus. The backbone of
  the Pareidoscope is the <a target='_blank'
  href='http://cwb.sourceforge.net/'>IMS Open Corpus Workbench</a>.
</p>
<h3>Legal</h3>
<p>
  The remainder of this page is in German due to German legal requirements.
</p>
